data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new span conversions change overload resolution. `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force binding to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches ensure the expression tree uses the `Enumerable` overload, which is representable in expression trees. The same fix applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays, which now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`.
